  "doc_id": "27518",
  "text": "The vacuole of yeast is a digestive organelle with storage functions. It contains a variety of hydrolytic enzymes, the pH optima of which vary from acidic to alkaline [CITATION_1] . The membrane of the vacuole contains a protontranslocating Mg2+-ATPase which generates a potential across the membrane of isolated vacuole vesicles and acidifies their interior [CITATION_2] . Since the internal pH of the vacuole in vivo has not been known, the role of the H+-translocating enzyme for the intravacuolar pH has remained unclear. Using FITC-dextran as a probe, we have here determined the intravacuolar pH to be mildly acidic, pH 6.5 (Fig. 2) . This is a considerably higher value than that (pH 4.7--4.8) found for the lysosomes of mammalian cells [CITATION_3] . The pH of the vacuole, like that of the endosomes, could be raised rapidly by ammonium chloride and CCCE Previously it has been reported that another lysosomotropic agent, chloroquine, is accumulated into the vacuole [CITATION_4] .",
